<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,295,702]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
DISTRIBUTION. Widely distributed in the Arabian Peninsula, extends northward to S 
<collectingCountry box="[1133,1208,399,424]" name="Jordan" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Jordan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Wittenberg, J." box="[1225,1423,399,424]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" pagination="59 - 64" refId="ref67856" refString="Wittenberg, J. (1992) First record of Arabian toad-head agamid (Phrynocephalus arabicus) in Jordan. Zoology in the Middle East, 7, 59 - 64. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 09397140.1992.10637625" type="journal article" year="1992">Wittenberg 1992</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[151,196,435,458]" name="Iraq" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Iraq</collectingCountry>
and marginally SW 
<collectingCountry box="[428,477,435,458]" name="Iran" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Iran</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,295,702]" box="[151,699,469,494]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
DISTRIBUTION IN 
<collectingCountry box="[349,405,470,493]" name="Iran" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">IRAN</collectingCountry>
. 
<figureCitation box="[420,502,469,494]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–13. 8" captionStartId="73.[151,264,1557,1580]" captionTargetBox="[171,1416,213,1516]" captionTargetId="figure-58@73.[151,1436,193,1536]" captionTargetPageId="73" captionText="FIGURES 8–13. 8. Laudakia erythrogaster. 9. Laudakia melanura. 10. Laudakia microlepis. 11. Laudakia nupta. Blue square denotes the type locality for L. n. fusca. 12. Phrynocephalus ananjevae. 13. Phrynocephalus arabicus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4929709" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4929709/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
. 
<collectingRegion box="[513,699,469,494]" country="Iran" name="Khuzestan" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Khuzestan Prov.</collectingRegion>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,295,702]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">HABITAT. Fine, windblown sand, sloping sand between mounds of vegetation and foot of large dunes. If threatened, it buries itself rapidly by lateral body oscillations.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,295,702]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
REMARKS. Observations of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Anderson" authorityYear="1894" box="[469,601,573,598]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Phrynocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="arabicus">
<emphasis box="[469,601,573,598]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">P. arabicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[641,710,573,598]" name="Oman" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Oman</collectingCountry>
showed that wherever suitable habitat appears this species can reach very high population densities (pers. obs.). There are no data available regarding the biology and natural history of this species in 
<collectingCountry box="[430,478,643,666]" name="Iran" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Iran</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
